### Steps to reproduce

Steps:
1. Open this link to live example: https://stackblitz.com/edit/ijwsrgbq?file=src%2FDemo.tsx (forked the first demo from https://mui.com/x/react-tree-view/rich-tree-view/lazy-loading/).
2. Wait for everything to be built and loaded
3. See that there are no Arrow/Chevron icons in the rendered view on the right side and there is no lazy loading taking place when clicking a tree item
4. Remove `-1, //` from line 33
5. Reload the view on the right side
6. See that there are Arrow/Chevron icons in the tree view and that lazy loading happens when a tree item is clicked


### Current behavior

Tree items for which `dataSource.getChildrenCount()` returns `-1` are not lazy loading when they are clicked, and there are no Arrow/Chevron icons. 

The [documentation](https://mui.com/x/react-tree-view/rich-tree-view/lazy-loading/) states:
> getChildrenCount(): Returns the number of children for the item. If the children count is not available for some reason, but there are some children, returns -1.

### Expected behavior

Tree items for which `dataSource.getChildrenCount()` returns `-1` have a Arrow/Chevron icon next to them, and are loading their children when clicked on.

### Context

I have tree items for which I know that they have children, but I do not know how many there are.

